## The `cn` + `cva` pattern — read this once

Every UI component in `components/ui/` follows the same shape. The canonical
example is `components/ui/text.tsx`. Mirror it:

```tsx
import { Slot } from '@rn-primitives/slot';
import { cva, type VariantProps } from 'class-variance-authority';
import { Platform, Text as RNText } from 'react-native';
import { cn } from '@/lib/utils';

const textVariants = cva(
  cn('text-foreground text-base', Platform.select({ web: 'select-text' })),
  {
    variants: {
      variant: {
        default: '',
        h1: 'text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight',
        // ...
      },
    },
    defaultVariants: { variant: 'default' },
  }
);

type TextProps = React.ComponentPropsWithoutRef<typeof RNText> &
  VariantProps<typeof textVariants> & { asChild?: boolean };

export function Text({ className, variant, asChild, ...props }: TextProps) {
  const Comp = asChild ? Slot : RNText;
  return <Comp className={cn(textVariants({ variant }), className)} {...props} />;
}
```

Why each piece matters:

- **`cn()`** runs `clsx` then `tailwind-merge`. Without it, conflicting
  Tailwind classes (e.g. caller passes `p-4` over a component's `p-2`) won't
  resolve correctly — both end up in the className string and the last one
  loses to specificity rules, not order.
- **`cva`** is just a typed factory for "given these variant props, return
  the right class string." Keep base classes outside the variants map.
- **`Slot`** + `asChild` lets callers swap the rendered element while keeping
  styles — the same pattern Radix and shadcn use on the web.
- **`Platform.select({ web: '...' })`** inside `cn()` is the canonical way to
  add web-only classes (e.g. `select-text`, `cursor-pointer`).
- **`TextClassContext` pattern** (see `components/ui/text.tsx`) — a React
  context exposing a className that children merge in. Use this when a parent
  needs to set typography for descendants (e.g. a `<Button>` setting text
  color/size for its label).

## Adding a new RNR component

**Prefer the CLI.** `components.json` is already configured:

```bash
cd frontend/apps/mobile
npx shadcn@latest add <component>     # e.g. button, card, input, dialog
```

Outputs land in `components/ui/`. The CLI knows about RNR's React Native
variants — it picks the right primitives and Tailwind classes for mobile.

**If hand-writing**, copy `components/ui/text.tsx` as the template:

1. Import the matching `@rn-primitives/*` primitive if one exists; otherwise
   the plain `react-native` component.
2. Define `xxxVariants = cva(...)` with sensible `defaultVariants`.
3. Compose via `cn(xxxVariants({ ... }), className)` so callers can override.
4. Expose `asChild` via `<Slot>` whenever it's reasonable to render-as.
5. For components that contain text (Button, Card, Alert), set up an
   `XxxTextContext` so the inner `<Text>` picks up the right variant.

**Theme tokens come from Tailwind classes**, not raw colors:
`bg-background`, `text-foreground`, `text-muted-foreground`, `border-border`,
`bg-primary text-primary-foreground`, etc. These resolve via CSS variables
in `global.css`, which means light/dark mode switching is free.

## Theming — two layers, know which to reach for

This codebase has **two parallel theme representations**. Picking the right
one matters:

1. **Tailwind / NativeWind classes** — use for anything you can style with
   `className`. Tokens like `bg-primary`, `text-muted-foreground` resolve via
   the CSS vars in `global.css`, so they automatically follow light/dark
   mode. This is the default for ~95% of styling.

2. **`useTheme()` from `@react-navigation/native`** — use for native chrome
   that can't take a className: tab bar tint colors, header colors, status
   bar. Returns `{ colors: { primary, card, border, text, background, notification } }`.
   The provider in `app/_layout.tsx` injects `NAV_THEME` from `lib/theme.ts`.

3. **`THEME` object at `lib/theme.ts`** — the raw HSL token map
   (`THEME.light` / `THEME.dark`). Only reach for this when you can't use
   Tailwind classes *and* `useTheme()` is awkward (e.g. computing a derived
   color in a non-component module). Rare.

**Dark mode is currently hard-coded** to `light` at `app/_layout.tsx`. To
enable: swap to `useColorScheme()` from `react-native`, then toggle the
`.dark` class on the root via NativeWind's `colorScheme` API so the CSS
variables flip.

## Expo Router conventions

- Any file under `app/` is a route. `app/foo.tsx` → `/foo`,
  `app/bar/baz.tsx` → `/bar/baz`.
- **Route groups** are folders wrapped in parens — `app/(tabs)/index.tsx`
  routes to `/`, *not* `/tabs/index`. The group only exists to share a
  layout.
- **Layouts** are `_layout.tsx` files. The root `app/_layout.tsx` is a Stack;
  `app/(tabs)/_layout.tsx` is the bottom Tabs.
- **Don't collide on `/`.** This app uses `app/index.tsx` as a
  `<Redirect href="/(tabs)" />` so the redirect runs before the tab bar
  mounts. If you add a real screen at `/`, remove the redirect and move the
  tab root.
- **Typed routes are on** (`experiments.typedRoutes: true` in `app.json`).
  `<Link href="/events" />` and `router.push('/events')` are both
  type-checked — invalid paths fail at build time, which is great but means
  any new route needs a fresh `expo` run for types to refresh.
- **Navigation: prefer `<Link>` over `router.push`.** If a press does
  *nothing but navigate*, use `<Link href={...} asChild>` around the
  pressable element — it gets real `<a>` semantics on web and the correct
  link a11y role for free. A bare `Pressable` whose only job was to call
  `router.push` is dead weight: drop it and let `<Link>` be the press
  target. Keep `router.push` only when navigation is a *side-effect of
  logic* — after an `await`, a form submit, or a conditional. To make a
  non-pressable container (a `Card`/`View`) tappable, wrap it as
  `<Link asChild><Pressable>…</Pressable></Link>` since a `View` can't
  receive `onPress`.

## Screen composition — route files stay thin

Route files under `app/` should be **thin containers**: route params, data
fetching (the generated `@pkka/api` hooks), and loading/error branching. The
actual layout/markup belongs in a presentational component under
`components/<feature>/` — mirroring `components/home/` (`hero`, `post-card`,
`cta-card`, `section-heading`) and `components/blog/` (`detail-header`,
`blog-post-view`).

- A screen that has grown a big presentational function inside it should
  extract that function into `components/<feature>/<name>.tsx`. Example:
  `app/blog/[slug].tsx` keeps only `useGetBlogPostBySlug` + state handling;
  the markup lives in `components/blog/blog-post-view.tsx`.
- **Keep components small and single-purpose.** If a component file is
  getting long or doing several unrelated things, split it. Favour many
  focused components over one large one — it matches the existing
  `components/` layout and keeps each file easy to scan.

## Icons

`lucide-react-native`. Named imports only; tree-shaking depends on it:

```tsx
import { Home, Calendar, LogIn } from 'lucide-react-native';

<Home color={color} size={size} />   // inside tabBarIcon, etc.
```

The `tabBarIcon` render prop already provides `color` and `size` — don't
hard-code them.

## Data layer (when you get there)

`@tanstack/react-query` is installed but no `QueryClientProvider` is mounted
yet. When the first network-bound screen lands:

1. Create the client at module top of `app/_layout.tsx` (`new QueryClient()`).
2. Wrap the `<Stack>` in `<QueryClientProvider>`.
3. Import generated hooks from `@pkka/api` — that workspace package owns the
   Orval-generated OpenAPI client (see commits `0c7600c`, `bdbf3a5`).

## Key file map

```
app/_layout.tsx              root Stack + ThemeProvider + PortalHost
app/index.tsx                redirect to (tabs)
app/(tabs)/_layout.tsx       bottom Tabs, uses useTheme() for native colors
app/(tabs)/{index,events,login}.tsx   tab screens
components/ui/text.tsx       canonical RNR pattern reference — read this first
lib/utils.ts                 cn() helper (clsx + tailwind-merge)
lib/theme.ts                 THEME (raw tokens) + NAV_THEME (React Navigation)
global.css                   CSS vars for light + dark
tailwind.config.js           token → CSS var bindings + animations
components.json              shadcn CLI config (aliases, style: new-york)
app.json                     New Arch, typed routes, React Compiler flags
metro.config.js              NativeWind Metro plugin wiring
babel.config.js              NativeWind Babel plugin + jsxImportSource
```

## Gotchas

- **Don't hand-write hex colors.** Use Tailwind tokens (preferred) or
  `useTheme().colors`. Hex values bypass the theme system and break dark mode.
- **Don't bypass `cn()`.** A bare template-string className loses
  `tailwind-merge`'s conflict resolution — class overrides silently fail.
- **Don't import from `react-native` when an `@rn-primitives/*` primitive
  exists.** You lose the accessibility wiring (`role`, `aria-*`, focus
  management) that the primitives bake in.
- **Don't put both `app/index.tsx` and `app/(tabs)/index.tsx` as real
  screens** — they collide on `/`. The redirect pattern is the resolution.
- **Don't add comments restating what good identifiers already say.** The
  project follows the repo-wide convention of comments-only-for-non-obvious-why.
